Here is an example code for a Discord bot using Discord.js v14 that has one command, "ban":
```
const { Client, GatewayIntentBits, SlashCommandBuilder } = require('discord.js');
const client = new Client({
  intents: [
    GatewayIntentBits.Guilds,
    GatewayIntentBits.GuildMembers,
    GatewayIntentBits.GuildBans,
  ],
});

client.login('YOUR_BOT_TOKEN');

client.on('ready', () => {
  console.log(`Logged in as ${client.user.tag}!`);
});

const banCommand = new SlashCommandBuilder()
  .setName('ban')
  .setDescription('Bans a user from the server.')
  .addUserOption(option => option.setName('user').setDescription('The user to ban.').setRequired(true));

client.guilds.cache.forEach((guild) => {
  guild.commands.create(banCommand);
});

client.on('interactionCreate', async (interaction) => {
  if (!interaction.isCommand()) return;

  if (interaction.commandName === 'ban') {
    if (interaction.options.getUser('user')) {
      const user = interaction.options.getUser('user');
      const reason = interaction.options.getString('reason');
      await interaction.guild.members.ban(user, { reason });
      await interaction.reply(`Banned ${user.tag} for ${reason || 'no reason'}.`);
    } else {
      await interaction.reply('Please specify a user to ban.');
    }
  }
});
```
Make sure to replace `YOUR_BOT_TOKEN` with your bot's token, which can be found in the Discord Developer Portal.

This code sets up a Slash Command called "ban" that takes one optional user argument and one optional string argument for the reason of the ban. When the command is invoked, the bot bans the specified user and replies with a message confirming the ban.

Note that this code uses the `guild.commands.create()` method to register the command for each guild the bot is a member of. If you only want to register the command for a specific guild, you can use the `guild.commands.create()` method in that guild's `on('ready')` event or in a separate function.

