Here's a simple C++ function that uses the `Convert::Markdown` library to convert Markdown to HTML:

```cpp
#include <string>
#include <convert/markdown.h>

std::string markdownToHtml(const std::string& markdown) {
    std::string html;
    Convert::Markdown md;
    html = md.convert(markdown);
    return html;
}
```

You'll need to install the `convert/markdown` library first. You can do this by running the following command in your terminal:

```
sudo apt-get install libuniversal-convert-perl
```

If you use a package manager other than APT, the command will be different.

Alternatively, you can use a regex-based solution, which might not be as accurate but is still a viable option:

```cpp
#include <string>
#include <regex>

std::string markdownToHtml(const std::string& markdown) {
    std::string html;
    html = std::regex_replace(markdown, std::regex("# (.*)"), "<h1>$1</h1>");
    html = std::regex_replace(html, std::regex("## (.*)"), "<h2>$1</h2>");
    html = std::regex_replace(html, std::regex("### (.*)"), "<h3>$1</h3>");
    html = std::regex_replace(html, std::regex(">(.*)</p>", std::regex::format, std::regex::ECMAScript), "<p>$1</p>");
    html = std::regex_replace(html, std::regex("\[(.*)\]\((.*?)\)", std::regex::format, std::regex::ECMAScript), "<a href=\"$2\">$1</a>");
    return html;
}
```

This function uses `std::regex_replace` to replace specific Markdown patterns with their HTML equivalents.

