public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        int[] arr1 = {1, 2, 3, 4, 5};
        int[] arr2 = {4, 5, 6, 7, 8};

        findCommonElements(arr1, arr2, 0, 0);
    }

    public static void findCommonElements(int[] arr1, int[] arr2, int i, int j) {
        if (i >= arr1.length || j >= arr2.length) {
            return;
        }

        if (arr1[i] == arr2[j]) {
            System.out.println(arr1[i] + " ");
            findCommonElements(arr1, arr2, i + 1, j + 1);
        } else if (arr1[i] < arr2[j]) {
            findCommonElements(arr1, arr2, i + 1, j);
        } else {
            findCommonElements(arr1, arr2, i, j + 1);
        }
    }
}
```

This program recursively traverses both arrays from the beginning until it finds a common element. If it finds a common element, it prints it and continues with the next elements in both arrays. If the current elements in both arrays are not equal, it moves to the next element in the array with the smaller element.

The time complexity of this solution is O(n + m), where n and m are the lengths of the two arrays, because in the worst case, it has to traverse both arrays once.
